snippet.title: [URDU] 2025 PMWC at EWC Grand Finals D3 | PUBG MOBILE WORLD CUP at ESPORTS WORLD CUP
snippet.description:
🏆 GrandFinals Teesra din | 3rd August.

2025 PUBG MOBILE WORLD CUP jo k ESPORTS WORLD CUP ka stage sajh chuka hai or wo faisly ki ghari aa chuki hai, aaj Grand Finals ka aakhri din hai Riyadh mein, jahan sirf ek team sab par bhaari padegi, taa k wo takht nasheen ho saken aur apna naam PUBG MOBILE ki tareekh mein hamesha ke liye likhwa saken.

Kai dino k intense competition ke baad, duniya ki top ki 16 PUBG MOBILE teamon ne apni jagah banayi hai final stage mein — glory, legacy, aur $3,000,000 ke prize pool ke liye. Yehi wo lamha hai jiske liye har team ne saalon se mehnat ki hai. Group Stage ki best teams aur Survival Stage k champions ab aamne samne honge is saal k sabse dhamakedaar showdown mein. "Teen din, SMASH RULE, aur sirf ek champion."

Safar ka ye aakhri moqa hai — lekin sirf ek team uthayegi trophy aur likhegi apna naam PUBG MOBILE ki tareekh mein. Aakhir kaar Grand Finals ka aghaz hony jaarha hai.

🔥2025 PMWC apko kyu miss nahe krna hai:

Yahan High pressure survival matches horhy hain!
16 teamain, or sirf 8 Grand Finals ka ticket hasil krengi!
Cheer karo apny favorite region aur team ko $3,000,000 prize aur taaj hasil krny k liye!
Grand Finals mein exciting SMASH RULE format hoga!

🔥 SMASH RULE kaise kaam karta hai?

Grand finals mai doosry din ke baad, Match Point Threshold set kiya jaega #1 ranked team ke points +10 add kr k.
Jo team ye points complete karegi, usay trophy jeetne ke liye ek aur match jeetna hoga kisi bad waly match mein. Agar kisi ne threshold match mein hi chicken kr liya to title nahi milega. Agar atharway match tak koi bhi team SMASH Rule se title hasil nahi kar pati, to mayari qawaneen ke mutabiq jis team ke qul adaad zyada honge wo team jeetegi.

📅 TOURNAMENT SCHEDULE

Group Stage: July 25–27
Survival Stage: July 29–30
Grand Finals: August 1–3

INDIA VS ENGALND Test 5 Day 4 Preview :

England need 324 more runs to win the match and the series, while India are effectively eight wickets away from leveling the series 2-2 (assuming Woakes won’t come out to bat).

With England 233/6, needing 35 more to win, and India just four wickets away from a series-levelling triumph, bad light and rain brought an early end to a gripping day. Chris Woakes was seen padded up in his whites yesterday, hinting he could bat today if needed despite the shoulder injury.

The final day promises high drama—will India snatch victory, can England hold their nerve, or will we witness a once-in-a-generation tie? Don’t blink. Every ball today could decide the series!


Early stumps on Day 4 due to a wet outfield. England need just 35 runs; India need 4 wickets (assuming Chris Woakes comes out to bat). Boos ring around the ground, but like the previous four matches in this series, the final Test will also head into a fifth day. 

The day started well for the visitors as they knocked over Ben Dukett and Ollie Pope in quick succession to push the hosts on the back foot. England were 106 for three at one stage and needed 268 runs to win. 

Joe Root and Harry Brook then played out of their skins and put on a stunning partnership of 195 runs for the fourth wicket.

Brook was on 19 when he gave India an opportunity but Mohammed Siraj, at deep backward square leg, took the catch and stepped on the boundary cushions. That triggered something in Brook and he unleashed his fury on the Indian bowlers.

In a bid to get quick runs, Brook miscued one to Siraj, who managed to hold onto it and ended his knock at 111. 

Root was steady as he brought up his 39th Test hundred. However, trying to steer one to third man, he edged the ball straight to the keeper.

INDIA VS ENGALND Test 5 Day 4 Preview :

England need 324 more runs to win the match and the series, while India are effectively eight wickets away from leveling the series 2-2 (assuming Woakes won’t come out to bat).

With England 233/6, needing 35 more to win, and India just four wickets away from a series-levelling triumph, bad light and rain brought an early end to a gripping day. Chris Woakes was seen padded up in his whites yesterday, hinting he could bat today if needed despite the shoulder injury.

The final day promises high drama—will India snatch victory, can England hold their nerve, or will we witness a once-in-a-generation tie? Don’t blink. Every ball today could decide the series!


Early stumps on Day 4 due to a wet outfield. England need just 35 runs; India need 4 wickets (assuming Chris Woakes comes out to bat). Boos ring around the ground, but like the previous four matches in this series, the final Test will also head into a fifth day. 

The day started well for the visitors as they knocked over Ben Dukett and Ollie Pope in quick succession to push the hosts on the back foot. England were 106 for three at one stage and needed 268 runs to win. 

Joe Root and Harry Brook then played out of their skins and put on a stunning partnership of 195 runs for the fourth wicket.

Brook was on 19 when he gave India an opportunity but Mohammed Siraj, at deep backward square leg, took the catch and stepped on the boundary cushions. That triggered something in Brook and he unleashed his fury on the Indian bowlers.

In a bid to get quick runs, Brook miscued one to Siraj, who managed to hold onto it and ended his knock at 111. 

Root was steady as he brought up his 39th Test hundred. However, trying to steer one to third man, he edged the ball straight to the keeper.
